ors famous saints from various parts of India. Various wall artworks illustrating the harmonious coexistence of various Indian religions can be found on the fifth floor. The sixth-floor honors and represents the various manifestations of the Goddess Shakti. The seventh floor displays Lord Vishnu, the Hindu goddess, in all of her avatars. Lord Shiva is honored with a shrine on the eighth and last floor since, in Hinduism, he is regarded as the ultimate god and the god of all gods. Visitors may view the stunning Haridwar skyline and the hills of Rajaji National Park from this 180-foot-tall temple's vantage point. At last, we can say that Bharat Mata Mandir is unquestionably one of the most attractive things to explore around Haridwar. 10. Maya Devi Temple The Maya Devi Temple, which honors Goddess Maya Devi, an avatar of Goddess Shakti, is one of the highlights of Haridwar. In the past, Haridwar was referred to as Mayapuri since the Goddess Maya was its patron. The Maya Devi temple completes the triad of Siddh Peeths in Haridwar. The Maya Devi temple in Haridwar is one of the country's oldest temples; it was constructed in the eleventh century. The temple is thought to have been constructed over the spot where Sati's heart and navel are said to have fallen in legend. Adi Shakti, the Goddess of heavenly force, is thought to take the guise of Goddess Maya. During Navratra and the Kumbh Mela, many worshippers of the Goddess come to seek her graces. Maya Devi is widely regarded as the principal Goddess of the holy city, and a pilgrimage is considered incomplete without receiving a glimpse of Devi. Among the 3 oldest temples in Haridwar that are still standing is the ancient Maya Devi Temple, along with Narayana-Shila and Bhairava Temple. Besides the idol of the Goddess Maya, the hallowed shrine also houses the idols of the Adi para shakti-inspired goddesses Kamakhya and Kali. According to popular belief, the holy temple is a Siddha peeth, which implies that the Goddess wh